Very roughly, to say that some object $Y$ in an $n$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is a colimit is to give a natural-in- $Z$ identification between morphisms $Y \rightarrow Z$ and some list of data of the form:

- 1-morphisms $x_{i}: X_{i} \rightarrow Z$, for some list of objects $X_{i}$;
- 2-morphisms $\xi_{j}$ whose source and target 1-morphisms are built by composing the $x_{i} \mathrm{~s}$ with 1-morphisms between the $X_{i} \mathrm{~s}$;
- 3-morphisms whose source and target 2-morphisms are built by composing the $\xi_{j} \mathrm{~s}$ with 2 -morphisms between the 1 -morphisms between the $X_{i} \mathrm{~s}$;
- and so on until $n$-morphisms;
- satisfying equations between those $n$-morphisms.

A limit is the same, except that one identifies morphisms $Z \rightarrow Y$ in terms of morphisms $Z \rightarrow X_{i}$ plus higher data. We will write $\mathcal{X}=\left(X_{i}, \ldots\right)$ for these data, and $Y=\operatorname{colim} \mathcal{X}$ for its colimit. Given such data $\mathcal{X}$, such a $Y$ is unique (up to a contractible space of choices) if it exists.

Suppose that $\mathcal{X}=\left(X_{i}, \ldots\right)$ is the data describing a colimit in some $n$-category $\mathcal{C}$, and let $Y \in \mathcal{C}$ be the corresponding colimit object. Suppose that $F: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \mathcal{D}$ is a functor of $n$-categories. Then there is natural data $F(\mathcal{X})$ describing a colimit in $\mathcal{D}$. The colimit of $F(\mathcal{X})$ in $\mathcal{D}$, if it exists, may not be $F(Y)$. Rather, the universal description of maps $\operatorname{colim} F(\mathcal{X}) \rightarrow Z$ implies that there is a canonical map $\operatorname{colim} F(\mathcal{X}) \rightarrow F(\operatorname{colim} \mathcal{X})$ in $\mathcal{D}$, which may not be an isomorphism. (If we had used limits instead, then there would be a canonical map $F(\lim \mathcal{X}) \rightarrow \lim F(\mathcal{X})$.) If it is an isomorphism, then $F$ is said to preserve the colimit described by $\mathcal{X}$. The data $\mathcal{X}$ describes an absolute colimit if the colimit described by $\mathcal{X}$ is preserved by all functors.
Example 4.2.1. Our main example is the condensate of a condensation monad. Indeed, suppose that $(X, e, \ldots)$ is a condensation monad with condensate $Y$. The proof of Theorem 2.3.2 identifies morphisms $Y \rightarrow Z$ and morphisms $Z \rightarrow Y$ with (right or left) condensation $e$-modules, and the data of condensation $e$-module is exactly of the form described above. So $Y$ is both a colimit and a limit. Furthermore, since functors take condensations to condensations, "taking the condensate" is absolute, both as a colimit and as a limit.

The 1-categorical theory of colimits is well-developed and well-known. For 2-categories, the theory of colimits is less well-known, but it is well-developed (see [nLaa] and references therein; note that though that the subtleties raised in [cM22] appear already in dimension 2). Our imagined $n$-categorical colimits include all variants of 2-categorical colimits, including what are usually called "lax" and "oplax" colimits - the different variants restrict in different ways the allowed sources and targets of the 2 -morphisms $\xi_{j}$.

When $n>2$, the theory of colimits in $n$-categories is not, as of the time of this writing, particularly well-developed. The best way to do so will be to recognize that a weak $n$-category is the same as an $(\infty, 1)$-category enriched in the $(\infty, 1)$-category of weak $(n-1)$-categories [Sim12, GH15]. In the world of strict 1-categories there is a well-developed notion of enriched, also called weighted, colimits [Kel05]. There will eventually be an analogous theory of enriched colimits in the $(\infty, 1)$-world, and $n$-categorical colimits will be a main example.

The 1-categorical versions of the following facts provide the foundations of the theory of 1categorical colimits by recasting colimits in terms of Yoneda theory. Our philosophy will be to assume that they hold in the eventual theory of $n$-categorical colimits, building on the higher Yoneda theory developed by [Hin20]. In the meantime, we will take fact (2) as our definition of Cauchy completion.
(1) Let $\mathcal{C}$ be an $n$-category. A presheaf on $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor of $n$-categories from $\mathcal{C}$ to the $n$-category Cat $_{n-1}$ of $(n-1)$-categories. Presheaves form an $n$-category called $\operatorname{Psh}(\mathcal{C})$. There is a fully faithful inclusion $\dot{x}: \mathcal{C} \rightarrow \operatorname{Psh}(\mathcal{C})$, called the Yoneda embedding, sending the object $Z \in \mathcal{C}$ to the presheaf $\dot{x}(Z): Y \mapsto \operatorname{hom}(Y, Z)$. (The letter $\dot{x}$ is the first letter of "Yoneda" when written in hiragana; its use for the Yoneda embedding was first suggested in [JFS17].) For any presheaf $T$, there is a natural equivalence $\operatorname{hom}(\dot{x}(X), T)=T(X)$.
